   "source": [
    "In Place Concatenation and Repetition - Lecture"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "4cf2ed62-2a26-4197-a00f-94efb5f02be4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Concatenation + \n",
    "\n",
    "Let's use Python's list as an example\n",
    "We can concatenate two lists together by using the + operator\n",
    "This will create a new list combining the elements of both lists\n",
    "\n",
    "l1 = [1, 2, 3]; id(l1) = 0xFFF100\n",
    "l2 = [4, 5, 6]; id(l2) = 0xFFF200\n",
    "l1 + l2 -> [1, 2, 3, 4, 5 , 6]; id(l1) = 0xFFF300"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "7f40f304-cc48-4a58-b4ff-241205be6c44",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In-Place Concatenation +=\n",
    "\n",
    "Recall that for numbers I have said that\n",
    "\n",
    "a = a + 10 and a += 10 mean the same thing\n",
    "\n",
    "True for numbers but not in general.\n",
    "True for numbers, strings, tuples -> in general for immutable types\n",
    "But not lists\n",
    "\n",
    "l1 = [1, 2, 3]; id(l1) = 0xFFF100\n",
    "l2 = [4, 5, 6]; id(l2) = 0xFFF200\n",
    "l1 += l2 -> [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]; id(l1) = 0xFFF100\n",
    "\n",
    "the list was mutated!\n",
    "\n",
    "For immutable types, such as numbers, strings, tuples the behavior is different.\n",
    "t += t1 has the same effect as t = t + t1\n",
    "Since t is immutable, += does not perform in-place concatenation\n",
    "Instead it creates a new tuple that concatenates the two tuples and returns the new object\n",
    "\n",
    "t1 = (1, 2, 3); id(t1) = 0xFFF100\n",
    "t2 = (4, 5, 6); id(t2) = 0xFFF200\n",
    "t1 += t2 -> [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]; id(t1) = 0xFFF300"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "a25a8ad5-fbb1-4e0c-80e4-da9d23a96eb3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In-Place Repetition *=\n",
    "\n",
    "Similar results for * and *= operator\n",
    "l1 = [1, 2, 3]; id(l1) = 0xFFF100\n",
    "l1 = l1 * 2 -> [1, 2, 3, 1, 2, 3]; id(l1) = 0xFFF200\n",
    "\n",
    "But in place-repetition works differently\n",
    "l1 = [1, 2, 3]; id(l1) = 0xFFF100\n",
    "l1 *= 2 -> [1, 2, 3, 1, 2, 3]; id(l1) = 0xFFF100\n",
    "\n",
    "the list was mutated!"
   ]
  },
